name: ethoxytrimethylsilane
Reason:
The molecule ethoxytrimethylsilane consists of an ethoxy group (C2H5O-) attached to a silicon atom (Si) that is also bound to three methyl groups (CH3). Each functional group influences the melting point as follows: 
- Ethoxy group: The presence of an ethoxy group, which is polar and can participate in dipole-dipole interactions, would generally raise the melting point relative to alkanes due to increased intermolecular forces. However, since silicon is less electronegative than carbon, the polarity of this bond is reduced compared to an oxygen bonded to carbon, thus this effect will be moderate. Estimate: +5 
- Methyl group on Si: Methyl groups attached to silicon contribute to lowering the melting point because they add bulkiness and reduce the overall ability of the molecule to pack efficiently in a solid state. However, the inductive effect of the silicon also can stabilize the arrangement to a certain extent. Estimate per methyl group: -5 
- Silicon atom: The Si atom itself has a larger atomic radius compared to carbon of a similar structure, potentially leading to a more open, less efficiently packed structure. This would tend to lower the melting point. Estimate: -10 
- The basic structural unit without any functional groups might be compared to ethane, which has a melting point of -183°C, as a rough base estimate.
